---
import ToolPage from '../../layouts/ToolPage.astro'
import TimestampConverterIsland from '../../islands/TimestampConverterIsland'
import { getToolMeta } from '@devkits/core'

const meta = getToolMeta('timestamp-converter')!
---

<ToolPage meta={meta}>
  <TimestampConverterIsland client:load />

  <section class="mt-12 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-4">How to Use</h2>
    <div class="prose prose-gray dark:prose-invert max-w-none text-sm leading-relaxed space-y-3">
      <p>
        Enter a Unix timestamp (in seconds or milliseconds) to see the equivalent human-readable
        date and time in UTC, your local timezone, and ISO 8601 format. Conversely, pick a date
        and time using the date picker to get the corresponding Unix timestamp in both seconds and
        milliseconds. The <strong>Now</strong> button fills in the current timestamp instantly.
      </p>
      <p>
        This tool is invaluable when reading log files, debugging API responses that return
        timestamps, comparing event times across different time zones, or writing database queries
        that filter by a specific date range. It also helps when setting expiry times for JWTs or
        cookies, where you need to calculate a Unix timestamp some number of hours or days in
        the future.
      </p>
      <p>
        Conversions are performed entirely in the browser using JavaScript's <code>Date</code>
        object. Your system timezone is detected automatically.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="mt-10 max-w-3xl">
    <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-6">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the difference between a Unix timestamp in seconds and milliseconds?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          A Unix timestamp counts the number of seconds elapsed since January 1, 1970, 00:00:00
          UTC (the Unix epoch). JavaScript's <code>Date.now()</code> returns milliseconds instead,
          so it is 1 000 times larger. Databases like PostgreSQL and languages like Python default
          to seconds, while JavaScript and many REST APIs use milliseconds — always check the
          magnitude to determine which unit you are working with.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">How do I get the current Unix timestamp in JavaScript?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          Use <code>Date.now()</code> for milliseconds or <code>Math.floor(Date.now() / 1000)</code>
          for seconds. In Node.js you can also use <code>process.hrtime()</code> for higher
          precision, but for most logging and API timestamp purposes <code>Date.now()</code> is
          sufficient.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">What is the Unix epoch and why does it start in 1970?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          January 1, 1970, 00:00:00 UTC was chosen as the reference point when the Unix operating
          system was being designed in the early 1970s. It was a convenient, recent date that fit
          within the integer types available on the hardware of the time. The choice has persisted
          as a de facto standard across nearly all modern computing platforms.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <h3 class="font-semibold text-gray-900 dark:text-gray-100 mb-2">When does Unix time overflow (the Year 2038 problem)?</h3>
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-600 dark:text-gray-400 leading-relaxed">
          32-bit signed integers can only represent Unix timestamps up to 2,147,483,647 seconds,
          which corresponds to January 19, 2038, 03:14:07 UTC. Systems still storing timestamps
          as 32-bit signed integers will overflow on that date. Most modern systems use 64-bit
          integers, which will not overflow for approximately 292 billion years.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</ToolPage>
